      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the goblin misstep! Let's dive straight into the science of achieving that dark, enticing crust on your sourdough. The Maillard reaction is indeed the key player here, and you're correct that aiming for the higher end of its temperature range can enhance the crust's color and flavor. However, it's important to note that as the temperature increases, the reaction can start to resemble caramelization, especially if the sugar content in your dough is high.\n\nTo achieve a dark crust without veering too much into caramelization, aim for temperatures around 150 to 165 degrees Celsius (302 to 329 degrees Fahrenheit). This range will maximize the Maillard reaction's effects, giving you that rich, golden-brown crust you're after, without the sweetness that comes with caramelization. Remember, the exact temperature can vary depending on your oven and the specific characteristics of your sourdough, so it might take a bit of experimentation to find the perfect spot.\n\nIn summary, while both the Maillard reaction and caramelization contribute to the crust's color and flavor, focusing on the higher end of the Maillard reaction's temperature range will help you achieve that dark, flavorful crust without the unwanted sweetness of caramelization. Happy baking, and may your",
